Yet the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies like the "credits" used to make progress in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, each time trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all net nodes are simultaneously depositors of the accounting book, auditors, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a dual encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bit coins are available in the public accounts accounts that are common throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task launched on computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, privileged to add this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computer "take" the new transaction and add a number before the whole is "hacked".
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zero at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay two times very fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated from the network and the other will remain without any link, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bit coins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundred millionth, which leaves a certain amount of room for manoeuvre...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with every improvement in the computing performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and lows.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin insoles stolen.
"The vulnerabilities used do not affect the actual protocol," said Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for payment with real money and uses the network Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors like Wikipedia refuse to donate this type.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of the bit coins are not circulated.
In November a "mega-final sale" was started.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," joins Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts Bitcoin into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by traders, and the latter must not install new terminals or computer programs.
You simply have to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in revising hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time to get through Bitcoin, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicted.
By the way, the ECB proposes in its report to re-evaluate the various risks currently regarded as high in the event of this currency's success.
