A Constitution with the Bread in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever in relation to the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To the surprise of everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the constituent assembly will adopt its final version on the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of his work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been relying on a provisional, multi-pronged text, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only created an even greater division of the country.
For his adversaries, the president is stuck in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trample the law".
On the side of his supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to refrain from their project to explain to the Egyptians the text section for section.
It is also a way for the President to find his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is raging throughout the country.
After reaffirming in an interview with the American Weekly Show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
With this intervention, the Egyptian people will be given an ultimatum to a hasty vote: 'Either they vote in favour of my draft or I maintain the unlimited power of authority', the latter should, after the Constitution has been adopted, supposedly put an end to it.
85 largely Islamist members of this constituent assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not responded to the request.
Shortly before the mid-November constitutional declaration, they turned away, because they believe that they have not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in all haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Moslem brothers.
It is no surprise that the articles were generally adopted unanimously.
The commentators also found it funny that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed during the period of prayer, as some members of the committee thought that the Pendeluhr of the constituent assembly did not go very well.
The text that was adopted last night consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew attention to itself, ultimately remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution and states that 'the principles of Sharia law are the main source of justice'.
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing 'the principles' with 'the rules', which would have made it possible to apply more strictly.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"hypocrisy" is what the Liberals regard as a propaganda strike.
They say that the constitution is being Islamicized through other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which provides an advisory function to the University of Al-Azhar, particularly in relation to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia law.
According to the Egyptians' specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, as 'the people who are called for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
You can see the first signs of a theocracy here".
Liberals’ fears are also fed by the fact that the next rebate of this university will be far less moderate than the one we have at the moment.
"At the moment, no concrete religious commitment can be seen.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics, some of whom have been educated in the French system, summoned Alexis Blouet, who writes a PhD on Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, it acknowledges that 'there can be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are exempt from the religious vocabulary.
This refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, Anm d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on it.'
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argue that they are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention is the powers of the army.
In line with the military’s desire, the review of the defense budget is not presented to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Nor will there be a ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as requested by the human rights associations.
The latter also share their concerns about the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The blasphemy affair is maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article refers to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the ban on torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While Egyptian President had to speak on television yesterday evening, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The heads of state will march on Saturday.
