"The big and powerful" leads to Moscow: migrants save money on language.
While MEPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading with forged certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only aim is to make money for the maintenance of the families left in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force, according to which each migrant worker must submit a test certified by Russian language knowledge.
Until now, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the local housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, the tests are to become compulsory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Agency.
Not only must language tests be carried out, but also tests in Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be shown both for the preservation and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is official.
This law also excludes people who received their training certificates and diplomas prior to the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sinn, problematic and protection of rights
The whole of the examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of Ethnology, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can carry out tests in all cities; more than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
On the other hand, before the law enters into force in the press, civil rights activists asked the following question several times: what does it actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills, both for Russians and for guest workers?
In particular, the answer to the spokesman for the migration agency is to reduce the number of forced labour.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says the head of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelew.
However, their rights must be protected from their departure.
Only organised recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
There are problems with migrants without jobs, education, language skills and medical examination.
Sebelew is convinced that a future migrant without linguistic knowledge will inevitably encounter those with bad intentions who put him in a dark, tight bark on the pretext of help, where he will stay with dozens of one-hour months without food and documents and create 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have many complaints from our migrants.
"In the home country you will be promised one, and on arrival you will be deceived, will receive your passports and will not receive the promised wage", confirms the head of the main administration for labour migration of the Tajian migration agency, Tolib Schwaripow.
Not shake, bosses!
Yet many of the citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to make their money in Russia admit that not only do they not manage the language of the destination country, but they can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmans, Uzbeks and Tajics can afford only reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed children, let alone buy decent clothes, shoes and school clothes.
As a teenager, these children take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It is difficult without language knowledge", give them.
'You feel humiliated and inferior.'
Civil rights defenders stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status must be tested.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "forbidden entry for unauthorised persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalisation costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A falsified registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The Russian police are aware that our documents are largely falsified and we are not registered, and then there are cases of blackmail.
"You want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea", says Tajique Umed Huschkadamow against journalists.
"Don't waste any costs on false papers."
Already on the day the law came into force, it emerged that not only the migrant registration documents can be falsified.
Some falsified certificates, which certify the absorption of the language test, have already been imposed by members of the Federal Migration Agency.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get it for free: every migrant who hoped to save the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that certificates cannot be bought simply, is shared by both officials and civil rights activists.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will be given time for a language course.
Moreover, newcomers are offered without language skills in areas where there is no need for active understanding with people.
