Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work its work was stopped from the start of the war.
Further articles on space appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Company (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company was made in 1954 in the November edition of the magazine Problemy, in which four major articles of space are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time, the first satellite technology projects were already in place, and it was clear that research into space would have a future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the 1951 International Space Federation, and indeed the PTA became a regular member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956 PTA has been instrumental in developing the highly successful meteorological rockets (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first start was made on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not exceed 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 the Błędów desert began flying tests with the two-tier RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and approximately 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for monitoring height winds.
In 1962, however, further development was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket was developed in 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as two-step rockets, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket have been developed (Meteor-1A, 1B and -1C), which differ from one another in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B with 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum height of the flight was 37 km in all three types.
In 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed in the aerospace institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of approximately 60 km.
Then the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 was also worth mentioning, and two years later the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites under the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second Intercosmonaut after the Czechs Vladimír Remek.
