Szabo: "Deutsche must play a greater role."
Germany abstained from the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in US relations, Berlin is thus balancing at a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
At the same time, however, I believe that it does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libyan uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on setting up a no-fly zone.
This was eventually imposed by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that is true.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that was, so to speak, managed by the US, to a German foreign policy.
What is more, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans therefore find themselves among the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still playing their part, but they are on the way to a more 'normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or the United Kingdom.
What does a 'normal' foreign policy mean specifically from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests, which are independent of those of the USA or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China and the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other big powers, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to upset the public, but also the elites, in Arab countries.
In any case, this is important.
But I would not want to attach too much weight to this, which is not a completely unilateral relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining on important decisions, such as the Palestine vote?
I believe that there is great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the United States.
Therefore, I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will actually show some respect.
Because it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that his interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly declared itself in favour of a veto.
Are there differences between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic politics, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has quite a lot of sympathy for the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, the government cannot publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so bright about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on one hand, and the position of the EU's main partners on the other?
I think that is precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little simpler for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and must instead drive things out of their own position.
That is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future, Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of its relationship with Israel.
That has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that the Germans understand that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player - does Germany want to play a leading role at all?
Or is Germany still struggling to lead?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to it, which is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
If, for example, we look at the euro crisis, there are different anti-German feelings every time Germany plays a greater role.
This does not make it easy for the Germans.
That is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be receptive to various neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now, the US’s influence in European politics is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who is left there?
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant to them and it makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America collaborate on the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
